We present observations of the strongly non-linear behaviour of a single circular soap film undergoing large-amplitude harmonic oscillations in the acoustic frequency range. In such a film, liquid is re-distributed towards its centre, which leads to striking mode formations and consequently to the ejection of droplets from the film. Both processes, liquid re-distribution and droplet ejection, finally result in the rupture of the film. Keywords: films; foams; vibrational properties
1. Introduction Soap films are elastic membranes of a very special kind: they consist of a thin liquid film of several nanometres to micrometres thickness, which is stabilised by surfactants (most commonly soap-like amphiphilic molecules).
Soap films have served as excellent models of vibrating membranes [1]. Their tension is due to surface tension and an interfacial elasticity, of which the latter is provided by the surfactant dynamics [2]. When analysing the vibrations of soap films, one needs to consider both the inertia of the liquid film and the inertia of the air moving with the film. The viscous dissipation within the oscillating film is, in general, negligible [1].
While the fundamental behaviour of a soap film under acoustic forcing is similar to that of standard elastic membranes, redistribution of liquid within the film and surfactant effects provide a range of physically relevant and esthetically striking effects. As a consequence, several types of acoustic responses are observed in soap films, which depend most significantly on the film thickness and the oscillation amplitude. For example, very thin films display strong and rapid recirculation (counter-rotating vertices) [3–5], while in films of sufficient thickness and oscillation amplitude, liquid is redistributed permanently from the nodes to the antinodes of the film. As a consequence, the oscillation amplitude in thick films is maximal at any forcing frequency. This mechanism is known as ‘‘self-adaptation’’ [6]. In some cases (for instance, for vertical soap films) soap film oscillations have been observed without thickness gradients [5].
