Figure 1. Overall film behaviour with time at constant frequency and amplitude: I. Initially the film is very thick and responds with chaotic oscillations. II. The film thins via the ejection of droplets. III. Once the film is sufficiently thin, large-amplitude oscillations are observed together with the formation of a liquid bulge in the centre of the film. IV. Eventually the film ruptures.
Until now, soap film oscillations have been studied at rather moderate oscillation amplitudes. In this article we report investigations into the strongly non-linear behaviour of soap films undergoing large-amplitude oscillations that lead to striking mode formations, instabilities (droplet ejection) and finally to film rupture.
We submit a horizontal soap film to an acoustic wave of strong amplitude, and we visualise the response of the film using a high-speed camera. Typical side views of the film response are presented in Figure 1. In general terms we observe that, after a transient regime (Figure 1(I)) in which liquid droplets are ejected (Figure 1(II)) from a very thick film, the soap film vibrates in phase with the forcing and is strongly deformed (Figure 1(III)). Furthermore, above a threshold amplitude, a liquid bulge forms in the centre of the vibrating film and oscillates simultaneously perpendicular to and in the plane of the film, displaying striking mode formations (Section 3). If the soap film is stable, the liquid bulge grows in time, and destabilises into droplets which are ejected from the soap film (Section 4). Both mechanisms, liquid redistribution and droplet ejection, finally lead to the rupture of the film (Figure 1(IV) and Section 5). This article focuses on the two latter stages (III) and (IV).
