3. Liquid bulge formation and modes
Observing the film from the side (Figure 3a), we find that despite its large amplitude it oscillates in a linear manner:
(1) the variation of the oscillation amplitude (measured at the centre of the film) is perfectly sinusoidal, as shown for one period in Figure 4a;
(2) All film shapes collapse on the same curve when normalised by the amplitude of the film centre, as shown in Figure 4b.
Both graphs of Figure 4 present the analysis of the example shown in Figure 3a. However, at the same time, a very pronounced liquid bulge (size of the order of 1 mm)
is formed at the centre of the film and oscillates in phase with the film (Figure 3b). Because of this additional weight, the shape of the oscillating film deviates clearly from being spherical, which would be the case for a film in which inertial forces are negligible with respect to surface tension forces.
