Interestingly, the observed shapes oscillate at the forcing frequency. This contrasts with most of the surface mode phenomena observed for individual drops [9], which oscillate sub-harmonically as the result of a parametric resonance driven by a spherical oscillation [10]. In our case, the surface modes are probably coupled in a nontrivial way to the vertical oscillations of the bulge reported above. The signature of these vertical oscillations can be seen in the second and fifth or sixth images from each sequence in Figure 5: the dark circular spot in the centre of the bulge represents a thicker part of the bulge. Furthermore, unlike in the case of isolated liquid drops, the bulge here can exchange liquid with the film; and also surfactant effects may play a role.
4. Droplet ejection The film oscillations with a central bulge, as described in Section 3, do not proceed indefinitely. As shown in the image sequence of Figure 6, the bulge grows continuously and finally becomes unstable, which leads to the ejection of droplets. These can in some cases be re-captured by the film or even cross the film without breaking it.

