Our recordings show that the creation of the droplets is very similar to the formation of drops from a dripping faucet (see, e.g. [11]), with a fast pinch-off followed by the formation of at least one visible satellite droplet. However, an interesting feature of the droplet ejection from an oscillating film is that it is controlled by surface tension and an inertial force, contrary to the usual case of a faucet where drops detach when gravity exceeds stabilising surface tension forces.
5. Film rupture As a result of liquid redistribution, ejection, evaporation and severe agitation, the lifetime of a soap film undergoing large-amplitude oscillations is generally rather short (order of a minute). The rupture mechanism in this case is very reproducible and shown in Figure 7: The film thins, particularly, strongly close to the boundary until it becomes a black film (typical thickness of a few tens of nanometer) and breaks. The rupture itself is very fast and of the order of a milli-second.
However, at very large applied acoustic amplitudes we observe a different rupture mechanism which is shown in Figure 8: The initial thick film undergoes very violent and

