chaotic oscillations which are accompanied by the ejection of big droplets and strong local distortions. In this case, the film breaks from a hole opening in its centre. The overall lifetime of the film is very short (order of a few seconds). The opening of the hole proceeds more slowly than in the previous case and generally takes a few milliseconds.
Although the location of the rupture is different in both cases, we believe that the rupture mechanism is fundamentally the same and originates in the local thinning of the soap film. In particular, the film breaks when its internal Marangoni elasticity does not balance the external stresses due to the fluctuation of the interface. At large amplitudes (Figure 8), the violent ejection of droplets in the centre of the film (i.e., at the antinodes of the vibration – see Section 3) induces strong and fast fluctuations of the film thickness. If Marangoni restoring stresses do not have time to build up, the soap film breaks in the weakest region, i.e., in the centre. At low amplitudes (Figure 7), the fluctuations of the film interfaces induced by the droplet ejection are weak enough (or slow enough) to be balanced by Marangoni stresses, therefore the centre of the film is stable. However, the re-distribution of the liquid slowly thins the film at its edges from where it consequently breaks.
