6. Conclusion
We have reported here a range of physical phenomena observed in soap films undergoing large-amplitude oscillations in the acoustic frequency range. For a clearer understanding of these mechanisms, much more systematic investigations are needed to determine the role of parameters such as the forcing frequency, the forcing amplitude, the initial film thickness, the waiting time after the soap film has been created, and the physico-chemical properties of the soap films, i.e., the role of the surfactants.
Studies of this type tackle a plethora of physical phenomena governing the hydrodynamic properties of soap films, but also of liquid foams. Of particular importance may be questions concerning foam stability. For example, several studies have shown that the collapse of foams can be initiated and controlled using ultrasonic waves [14,15]. Coupling such kind of investigations with those of the rupture mechanisms of an individual soap film, carries the promise of providing important ingredients for the theoretical modelling; in particular for the influence of the physico-chemical properties of the system. Equally, investigations of the rupture of soap films under an acoustic forcing may allow to better understand the absorption of shock waves by liquid foams [16].

